      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/03/a-reasonable-question/#comment-17902"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-05-13T00:51:29-04:00">Thursday, May 13, 2010 at 12:51 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>when restaurant chefs say &#8220;plastic wrap&#8221; they mean the heavy duty PVC film used in restaurants not saran wrap..</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-17902' data-commentid="17902" data-postid="860" data-belowelement="comment-17902" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Anonymous" aria-label='Reply to Anonymous'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-17903" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/17360646101282742552" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Sigrid</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/03/a-reasonable-question/#comment-17903"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-05-13T13:01:46-04:00">Thursday, May 13, 2010 at 1:01 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>One problem I get using the &#8220;stir occasionally&#8221;-method is a skin that builds on top and, being stirred back under, forms lumps. I think I stir every 10 minutes but that&#39;s enough time for the skin to build.</p>
    </div>

